{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170847/1946051601/0279.xml":{"full_text":"MARKET WAITING\nTO SEE RESULTS\nOF LEWIS TRUCE\u2019\nStocks Drift Lower as Specu\nlators Decide to Sit It Out\n-\u2014Ayres Sees Need for\nStronger U. S. Control\nM nil .Street CorrnKpondenc*\nOt 'llie Republican\nNew York. May 11 When John L.\nI.ewla consented Erldaj to a two\nweek truce in the coal strike, the\naiock maiket responded with a sharp\nadvance. Today speculators and in\nvestors were standing on the side\nlines waiting to see what Is going Io\nhappen whe.n the truce ends. A small\nhandful of specialties advanced a\npoint or more today, hoi the market\nas a whole drifted fractionally lower\non small volume. Between 1 and 2\nfi-yo. .Im i\"-\nUOO shares.\nPointing out that coal is the fuel\nUsed by most of electric uiiliiies, that\nmost locomotives hauling food and\nraw materials burn coal, that pro\nduction of iron and steel is dependent\non coal, thai much manufacturing\ndepends on coal for power, that coal\nis a domestic fuel used in many mil\nlions of homes. I^eonard P. Ayres,\neconomist of the Cleveland Trust Co.,\nsays in his May Iwnk letter:\n\"Under a Republican form of gov\nernment no one individual ought to\nhave power to suspend, when he so\nwishes, the production of a commodity\nthat is a basic necessity in our na\ntional well being, and then to restore\nproduction when and it he sees fit to\ndo so. Because this is happening to us\nour republican form of government is\nbeing fundamentally impaired.\nGreater Than Government\n\"We shall find no solution through\ndenouncing the man. The wrong lies\nin the short-comings of laws which\npermit him and his fellow labor dic\ntators to exercise their almost un\nlimited powers without regulation or\ncontrol. The government has built up\nthese powers through years of de\npression and boom, of peace and war.\nand now having failed to regulate the\nlabor dictators, the government is\nsuddenly astonished to find that they\nhold and exercise greater powers than\nit possesses.\"\nTwo alternative courses are open to\nthe government, it is pointed out, one\nto nationalize the mines and the coal\nmining industry, the other \"to enact\nessential legislative changes mostly\nconsisting of amendments to existing\nestablished law. They should regu\nlate. and restrain all threatened\nstrikes that might be against the\npublic interest because they involve\non a large scale the public's health,\nfood, light, power transportation, or\nsafety. They should provide that\nunions must bargain in good faith as\nlaws now insist that management\nmust. They should clearly define il\nlegitimate objectives of strikes.\"\nAyres says that according to the\nindustrial production Index compiled\nby his bank, physical volume, of in\ndustrial production for November,\nwhen strikes were just starting, was\n12.1 per cent above the computed\nnormal level; that it declined to\n.8 per cent above in December; to\n1.0 per cent above in January; to 6.2\nper cent below normal for February,\nand that the preliminary figure for\nMarch is back to 15.2 per cent above\nnormal, adding;\nStrikes Are Blamed\n\"Most of the declines in the index\nin recent months have been the re\nsult of strikes. The output of indus\ntries that have been shut down, such\nas automobile and steel plants, has\nbeen greatly curtailed while other in\ndustries that furnished them with\nsupplies have also had to decrease\noutput. On the other hand many\nindustries, particularly the nondurable\ngoods producers, have continued to\nexpand production. The sharp re\ncovery in March seems th indicate\nthat in the absence of strikes in\ndustrial production could be greatly\nIncreased.\u201d\nAccording to an old, simple and\naeldom used test, prices of common\nstocks are now high enough to be in\nthe danger sone, the Cleveland econo\nmist says, \u201cbut still they are far from\nbeing unprecedentedly high.\" A chart\nis included going back to 1900 giving\nsquare roots of annual averages of\ndata of industrial stocks based on\nthe axerage for 1935-39 taken at 100.\nThe chart covers the tops of all of\nthe bull markets since the beginning\nof this century except the one which\nended in 1929 and the bottoms of nil\nthe bear markets except that of 1932.\nThe conclusion Is:\n\"There are at least three good rea\nsons why this present bull market\nmight, continue. One is the general\npressures of inflation which result in\nspeculators having money to venture\nsnd which in some cases impel them\nto buy stocks as a hedge against, in\nflation. A second reason why stock\nmarket prices might continue upward\nfor some period of time, is that we\nhave in this country a combination of\nproductive capacity and of accumu\nlated shortages of goods which gives\npromise of producing a business\nboom. A third reason is that the\ncontinuation of artificially low inter\nest rates is making the return on\ngood bonds so low that stocks are\ngiven increased relative value.\u201d\nR. L. BARNL'M.\nBANKING RESOURCES\nDOUBLE \u20194O FIGURES\nNew York, May 14\u2014(AP)\u2014 Banking\nresources in the United States more\nthan doubled during the five war\nyears of 1940 to 1945. it wes an\nnounced today in a consolidated state\nment of all federally and state char\ntered hanks prepared by the state\nhank division of the American Bank\ners association.\nOn December 31. 1945. the state\nment shows total resources of 11.553\nbanks in continental United States\nreached s record peak of $177,364.-\n700.000, compared with December 31,\n1940, when consolidated assets of 14.-\n892 active banks were $84,980,578,000.\nAt the end of 1944 there were 11.535\nactive banks which reported resources\nof $152,016,421,000.\nLoans apd discounts outstanding\non December 31, 1915. Increased to\n$30,330,566,000 over the $23,741,244,000\nreported on December 31, 1940. The\ncapital account of the banks in\ncreased more than two billion dollars\nduring the war years, from $8,337.-\n236.000 on December 31. 1940. tn $lO,-\n679,246.000 on December 31. 1945.\nJohn A. Coleman Reelected\nExchange Board Chairman\nNew York. May (AP) \u2014John\nA Coleman wa* reelected today chair\nman of the board of governors of the\nNew York Stock exchange, the flrat\nman to hold that post tour terms.\nColeman started with the exchange\nSo years ago as a page boy on the\nfloor, later buying a membership.\nOut-of-town members elected to the\nhoard included: Howard Butcher. Jr..\nPhiladelphia reelected); Russell E.\nGardner, Jr., St Louis returning from\nmilitary service): Joseph Hinshaw.\nAeiroit; and William Bayne, Boston.\nFINANCIAL\nRETAIL DEALER SAYS\nSAUSAGE FOR RELIEF\nSecretary of National Meat\nAssociation Recommends\nKeeping Better Grades for\nDomestic Market\nChicago, May 13\u2014(AP>\u2014 George R.\nDressier, secretary of the National\nAssociation of Ketal) Meat Dealers,\ntoday recommended sending sausage\nand similar meals for relief feeding\nabroad while holding better grades\nfor domestic consumption.\ncontinued Secretary of Agriculture\nAnderson was \u201cout of line\" in asking\nfarmers to cut their fall pig crop by\n10 per cent to save grain.\n\"We should be increasing produc\ntion by using every available acre of\nlend to produce grain so we can have\nmeat and grain enough for all pur\nposes.\" Dressier said.\nReferring to meat for relief, he\nsaid, \u201cInstead of sending carcasses\nand choice primal cuts abroad, they\ncould ba m\\ fd foi domi di Ie m i rkets\nThie. \u00abgq\u00bbverMnr>ent a mnM kirmi\u2019. ,<i.-\npend on sausage and manufactured\nproducts for relief feeding. Such items\nhave just as much food value as the\nchoice cuts of meat, and it would be\na saving to American taxpayers.\nEXCHANGE SHOWS\nSOME STRENGTH\nLight Selling Pressure Puts\nMany Leaders in Losing\nBrackets Buying Based\nOn Earnings, Labor Hopes\nNew York. May 13 (A P) \u2014Individ-\nualized strength persisted in today\u2019s\nstock market although light selling\npressure put many leaders in the losing\nbracket.\nBuying again was based partly on\nearnings, dividends, slitup possibilities\nand faint hopes of labor adjustments.\nThe back-to-work move of the coal\nminers propped sentiment to a certain\nextent but skeptics continued to lighten\ncommitments on the idea that a final\nsettlement in the bicuminous field\nmight not halt strikes elsewhere. Real\nization that second quarter corporate\nrports generally would make poor\nreading for stockholders also inspired\ncaution.\nDealings were relatively quiet\nthroughout. Transfers of 1.250.000\nshares compared with 1,820.000 Friday.\nDeclines running to 2 or more points\npredominated at the close. Of 996 issues\nregistering. 444 fell and 355 advanced.\nAmong scattered favorites were com\nmercial solvents, up 2% at $31.62; Yale\nTowne 3% at $60.25. General Tire 2*4\nat $56.75. American Telephone 1 at\n$194.50, Santa Fe 1 at $108.75, Pepsi-\nCola 1 at $35.25. Omnibus Corp. 1%\nat sl7 and Panhandle Producing 1% at\n$12.75.\nCurb advancers included Powdrell\nAlexander, Canadian Industrial Alcohol\n\"A\u201d and \u201cB,\u201d Jeannette Glass and\nCreole Petroleum. Turnover here was\n480.000 shares versus 670.000 in the\npreceding full session.\nCHRYSLER CORP. BUYS\nGRAHAM-PAIGE PLANT\nWillow Run. Mich.. May 13 <AP)\nChrysler Corp, has purchased for $2.-\n750,000 the former Graham-Paige Mo\ntor Corp.'s plant at Dearborn. Mich.,\nJoseph W. Frazer. Graham-Paige\npresident, announced today.\nGraham-Paige vacated the factory\nlast November when it moved its\nmanufacturing facilities to the Wil\nlow Run plant, which it occupies\njointly with the Kaiser-Frazer Corp.\nEARNINGS STATEMENTS\nNew York. May 13 -(AD) Uniled\nAircraft Corp, and its wholly owned\nsubsidiary, United Aircraft Service\nCorp., today reported operations for\nthe March quarter resulted in a net\nloss of $505,921. compared with a net\n[profit of $3,547,781, or $1.21 a common\nshare, after preferred dividend re\nquirements. in rhe same 1945 period.\nj The loss for the 1946 period is after\nLa credit of $1,828,108 resulting from a\nreduction of federal taxes applicable\n(o prior years as provided for by the\ncarryback provisions of the internal\nrevenue code.\nDirectors of United Aircraft today\ncut the dividend on its common stock\nto 50 cents from ?1 paid in recent\nquarters. The dividend is payable June\n15 to stock of record May 31.\nSperry Corp.\nNew York. May B\u2014(AP)~The\nSperry Corp, 'has the strongest\nfinancial position in its history,\u2019\u2019 bur\nexpects little profit on current orders\nbecause of hig-her costs and price re\nstrictions, Thomas A. Morgan, chair\nman. said today. In the annual report\nto stockholders Morgan said net in\ncome for 1945 amounted to $6,954,487,\nor $3.45 a capital share, after taxes\nand the addition of $1,000,000 1o the\nreserve for postwar adjustments.\nwhich now amounts to $12,000,000.\nThis compared with 1944 net of $7.-\n725.138. or $3.83 a share, after taxes\nand a $3,750,000 credit to the postwar\nreserve.\nContinental Oil\nThe Continental Oil Co. reported\ntoday for the March quarter con\nsolidated net earnings of $2.606.354.\nequal to 56 cents a capital share, com\npared with $3,448,359, or 74 cents a\nshare in the like 1945 period. The\n1946 net Included a profit of $254,235\nresulting from the. sale of certain\nassets.*\nAdam Hat\nAdam Hat stores reported for the\nfirst quarter record sales of $4,136,333,\na 37.5 percent gain over $3,007,481\nlast year, w'hlch resulted in a peak\nnet income for the three months\nended March 31 of $260,039, equal to\n62 cents each on 418.499 common\nshares outstanding. This represented\nnan increase of 125 per cent over the\n'5115,230 net profil. equal to 27 cents\n[on a similar basis in the like quarter\niof 1915.\nReo Motors\nj Reo Motors reports for the March\nquarter net profit of $263,626. equal\ni to 55 cents a share, against $716,756,\nor $1.48 a share .in the 1945 period.\nAbbot Laboratories\nNorth Chicago. HL, May 8\u2014 (AP)~\nAbbott Laboratories reported today\nnet. first-quarter profits was $2,835,-\n398. or $1.65 a share of common stock,\ncompared with $771,382. or 44 cents a\nshare, for the first threb months\nof 1945.\nL. C. Smith, Coronn\nL. C. Smith Corona Typewriters,\ninc., reports for the March quarter\nI net income of $204,560. equal to 63\ncents a share on 322.569 shares out\nstanding, against $5T,565. or 11 cents\na share, on 276.237 shares outstanding\na year ago.\nLIMBER PRODI t HOX OFF\nSeattle. May 13 (AP) Cumu\nlative lumber production on the West\nCoast for the 17 weeks of this year,\nas reported to the West Coast Lum\nbermen\u2019s association today, aggre\ngated 1.950.225.000 board feel, com\npared with 2.425.392.000 in the first\nI 17 weeks of last year and ?.7\u00bb2,5a4.000!\n[in the corresponding period of 1944.1\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, MAY 16, 1946\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET\nSale of Stocks\nNew York Stock exchnnire\nNew lurk Curb exchange 180,0011\nHoxfon Stock exchontre 15,825\nNet\nSale* in 100 High Low Clone Chg\nA\n1 Abbott Lab 82% 82% 82% -1%\n4 ACF-Brlll Mot 16% 15% 15% t\nI Arms Stl 46% 46\u20194 46\nII Adame Exp 22% 22% 22%\n3 AddreMog Mult 38% 38 38 t\n3 Admiral Corp 13% 15% 15% 4-\n10 Air Reduction 54% 53% 33%\u2014\n3 Aldens Inc 45 45 45\n11 Alaska Juneau 8% 8% H%\u2014\n36 Alleghany Corp 6% 6% 6%\n7 Do pf 61 6b% 61\n13 Alleg Lud Stl 53% 52% 53% b\n1 Allen Industries 22% 22% 22%\n4AI Chern A Dye 203% 202 203%+ 1\n.'I Allied Kid 26% 25% 26%\n8 Allied .Mills 38% 38 38\n17 Allied St is 61% 60% 61%\n3 Do pt 105 104% 10 4% 4\n16 Allis Ch Mfg 55% 54% 55\n14 Amal Leather 10% lo 1 io%\n6 A mereda Pet 171 160 171 r 2\nI Am Ag <\u2019h Del 45 45 45\n118 Ain Airlines 18% 17% 17%\nI Ain Bomb I a 4\n5 Am Brake Shoe 62 61 61\n1.50 Do pf 130 130 130 E\n1\" Am Cable A Rad 13% 13% 13%\n9 Am Can 96% 95% 95%\u2014 1\n1.70 Do pt 201% 201 201\nI Am Car A Edy 68 68 68\n8 Am Ch 