ooo shares.\nOHIO co. plT\\ approved\nPlu.adelphta. May 14 (AP) The.\nSecurities and Exchange commission\n'approved today a refinancing program\nof Ohio Public Service Co. providing\nf \u00bbr the issue and sale at eompetitive\nbidding of $32,000,000 of first mortgage\nlends, due .1976. and 156.300 shares\n>f SIOO par value cumulative piv\nferred stock The company also will!\nj issue and sell $6,000,000 of irs serial\nnotes at competitive bidding and $5\n208.300 aggregate par value of addi\ntional common stock, to its parent.\nCity\u2019s Service Power and Uight Co..\nU niRRCTORS REFLECTED\nSalt Uko City. May H-iAD\nStockholders of the Union Pacific:\ni railroad reelected 15 directors at the\niannual meeting today*\nMARKET IS QUIET;\nINDUSTRIALS FAIL\nTO HOLD ADVANCE\nClose Off .72 as Rails Decline\n.33 Big Business Feels\nResult of Having No Goods\nlo Sell\nW all Street I orrespondenre\nOf The Republican\nNew York. May 13 With the ei\nception of a few specialties, the stock\nmarket today was Irregular and quiet.\nFailure, of industrials to make a new\nrecovery high was disappointing. Ea\nrablishing a new recovery closing\nhigh on April 18 at 208.15, the indua-\nI trial average, on the growing \u00bben\nousnesa of the coal strike, declined to\nI 200.65 on May 6. closing Saturday on\nine coal strike truce at 208.06. At the\n\u201cnd of the first hour thia morning\nindustrials were down .51. after wftJtW\nthere was a slight reenverv followed\noy ano nev decline to a closing oit\n.72. Raila finish\u2019d down .33.\nShortages in many direction* have\ndislocated production and supply in\nindustry to the point where rhe out\nhx>k for the remainder of this year\nis sour, according to Wall street\u2019s\nweekend information from Washing\nton That viewpoint appears to be\nconfirmed by today s news rbat busi\nnew firm? with not enough to sell\n9re canceling radio advertising con\ntracts after having asked themselves.\nWhy spend all that money pushing\nproducts we can\u2019t sell because we\ncan\u2019t make them?\u201d\nWestinghonse Off Air\nGeneral Foods, one of radio's heavi\nest spenders, according to todays\nnew*, is making a heavy cut in its\nradio budget. Westinghouse on June\n30 will drop its Sunday afternoon pro\ngram. which costs $1,300,000 a year.\nCelanese Corp, whose \u2019Great Mo\nments in Music\u2019* has coat $1,500,000\nannually will go off rhe air when its\ncontract expires June 26. Armour\nCo. has announced it is canceling its\ncontract June 3 General Motors is\ndropping irs NBC Symphony of the\nAir\u2019\u2019 in July. Chrysler ends its con\ntract at the end of this month. Other\nlarge corporations that either have\nended their radio contracts or plan\nto do so in the near future include\nGeneral Electric. Procter Gamble,\nLever Bros, and Bristol-Myere.\nOn top of this news a report comes\nfrom Washington that black markets\nare growing like wildfire. It is stated\nthat black markets exist today all\n:hp way down from manufacturers tp\njobbers, wholesalers, retailers, con\nsumer buyers; that black marketing\nis difficult to control being done not\nby gangsters but by men who want\nto keep their customers and stay in\nbusiness.\nThat shortexist in meat, but\nter, shirts and a long list erf other\nconsumer goods is a ma tier of com\nmon knowledge. Where do the black\nmarkets get the stuff they sell? They\n\u2666et meat butter, shirts, etc., by pay\ning higher than ceiling prices. The\nwar is over an! to get what they\nwant, consumers with more spend\ning power than ever before existed\nin any country are willing to pay\nthe prices asked for the Limited sap\nply in a black market.\nBut is the business outlook for the\nremainder of 1946 resulting from\nshortages as sour\u2019\u2019 as painted today\nfrom Washington? Some people in\nth<* financial district here say no.\nThere is not the slightest doubt but\n\u2019hat the situation existing today from\nshortages is bad. But it is being cor\nrected and unless something unex\npected happen\u00ae will show in the.\nmonthly industrial production index\nof rhp Federal Reserve board a\u00ab soon\nas the coal strike is settled, assum\ning that there will not be a railroad\nstrike, or that if there is one it\nwill be short lived.\nWashington Find* Ont\nImmediately after the war ended in\nAugust. President Truman, backed\nh> high administration officials, an\nnounced that the government's re\nconversion policy would be to favor\nhigher wages to com* out of the\nprofits of business. At that time peo\nple in Wall street familiar with the\neconomic facts of life said in effect.\nIt can\u2019t he done. What will happen\nwill be dislocation of business, short\nages. black markets. Businessmen just\nwon\u2019t produce goods unless they are\nallowed to make a profit. President\nTruman and his reconversion wage\nprice policy advisers, it seems, have\ngot to find that out the hard way.\nIn the meantime a monkey wrench\nwill be thrown into the reconversion\nmachinery.\u2019\u2019\nThat is exactly what did happen\nuntil the administration, with The\nsteel mills operating at only 54 per\ncent of capacity, agreed to let steel\nmanufacturers raise their selling\nprices to offset the increase In wages\nof steel workers sponsored by the\nadministration. That reversed the ad\nministration\u2019s original ho\u2019d the price\nline policy. Since ths steel strike was\nsettled, every day sees more and more\nprice increases authorized by The OPA.\nD slocation of business such as ex\nis:s today through shortages cannot\nbe corrected overnight. But with\nPresident Truman and bis reconver\nsion advisers now recognizing facts\nof life we are on the right road to\ncorrect shortages, check black mar\nkers and hold back price inflation.\nAn antidote to inflation m a situ\nation I kp the present.\u201d The Federal\nReserve bank o? New York says to\nday in :s annual report, \u201cis a large\nand balanced output witrh rising pro\nductivity per worker. To this objec\ntive governmental and business poli\ncies must be mainly directed, and upon\nour success n achieving it will largely\ndepend whether we shall lay the foun\ndation in 1946 for a period of orderly\nprosperity or have an inflationary\noutburst terminating in depression.**\nR L. BARNL'M.\nINVESTMENT COMPANIES\nENLARGE CASH HOLDINGS\nNew York. May 5 AP>\u2014 Tn vest\nment com pa as a group increased\ntheir rash positions moderately dur\nins rhe first quarter of 1948. the\nNational Association of Investment\nCompanies reported today.\nTo*tl cash and U S. government\nbond holdings of rhe .30 largest broad\nly dive sffipd funds totaled $154,000.-\n000 or about 10 3 per cent of total\nissprg of $1,497,000,000 on March 31.\nThis compared with $118,000,000 or\n9.1 per cent of assets of $1,431,000,000\nthree months previous.\nSixteen out of 29 securities In\nwhich purchases predominated we\u2019-e\nin four industries\u2014oils, utilities, rails\nand aviation \u2014although sales pre\ndominated in other securities within\nrhe same groups.\nMost widely-held stocks on March\n31 included Montgomery Ward. North\nAmerican Co.. Standard Oil (NJ),\nKennecott Copper and Chrysler Coro.\nMoat widely-held bonds for the 30\nfunds, which invest chiefly In com\nmon stocks and other equity-type\nsecurities, were reorganization mils\nincluding Missouri Pacific System. St\nLouis-San Francisco. Baltimore -4\nOhio. St Paul and Rock Island\n.Pacific.\nNew Vo k. M\u00bby 13 AP) Steel\noperations this week will be at th*\nlowest point since the middle nf 1989\nexcept for th* drastic curtailment dur\ning the steel strike early thia year.\n13","height":"25974","width":"19285"}}
